##Wuhan Hotel Person: Guards the medical staff and the volunteer, is guards itself

Over a month, more than 300 hotels in Wuhan have provided more than 100,000 nights of accommodation for more than 10,000 health care workers and volunteers. Without proper replenishment and relief, they will not be able to survive.

By Wan Pei, CAIJING reporter

Editor | Song Wei

The city of Wuhan, the epicenter of the outbreak, has been sealed off for more than a month, posing unprecedented challenges for hoteliers in the city. Because the passenger flow tends to zero, they can not operate to cause "the grain does not receive" , must still bear the corresponding rent, the manpower and so on cost.

More realistically, the closure of the city, the suspension of Public Transport and the physical fragmentation of Wuhan into numerous isolated units, has made the commute of health care workers a challenge. Under these circumstances, even though they face considerable financial pressure, the hoteliers are the first to step forward to provide shelter for the doctors and nurses in the front line.

This means that, in addition to the original economic losses, the owners have to bear the additional monthly water and electricity charges of tens of thousands of yuan. Zhao Min, a hotel worker, told Caijing that he did not dare to do any careful accounting. Zhao Min says he now wakes up with a 200,000 yuan loan on him, and in order to make ends meet, he has to raise money from relatives to make up the shortfall.

Zhao Min was initially involved with the rescue of more than 300 types of Wuhan hotels, they spontaneously organized the "Wuhan Medical Hotel Support Alliance" (hereinafter referred to as "the alliance") . Founded on New Year's Eve (Jan. 24) , the alliance has provided more than 100,000 overnight accommodations for more than 10,000 health care workers and volunteers over the past month.

But the epidemic continues, some hotels have been unable to afford high costs, had to withdraw from the rescue plan. On January 31, the alliance announced that 159 individual hotels, bed and breakfast, apartments and small hotel chains in the Wuhan area would no longer receive medical staff and guests.

Since the start of the alliance, hotel owners have spent more than 2.5 million yuan on utilities and Linen alone, said Li Chao, a CO founder of the alliance and founder of global travel. Most hotel staff are exhausted, and the physical and sanitary conditions of the hotel are stretched to the limit, which puts the operation and service of the hotel at great risk.

So far, Wuhan, there are more than 50 small and medium-sized hotels in the struggle to adhere to. "It's comforting, " Zhao Min quipped after hearing the figure. "I wonder if I'm the only one left. "

1

To help guard Wuhan

At 10 a.m. on January 23, Wuhan was hit with the pause button.

In this isolated epidemic city, on the one hand is highly infectious and unpredictable virus, on the other hand is increasing financial, material, medical pressure. Those in the city must fight to save themselves. And a bunch of hotel people came together.

Xiao Yaxing, a girl born after 1990, is the first founder of the alliance. At the beginning of the epidemic, she took four hotels out of her hands to solve the accommodation problem of medical staff, and through the network, Ota Platform to find air conditioning, suitable conditions to join the hotel.

The call was quickly answered by more than 300 hotels. Over the past month, the alliance has provided more than 100,000 overnight accommodations for more than 10,000 health care workers and volunteers, according to the alliance.

In order to solve the shortage of materials in the operation, she also transformed the hotel into a temporary warehouse, goods from all directions transferred to her here, masks, convenience food, disinfectant, etc. , and then by her deployment, distribution.

The Alliance has become a transit point in the fight against the epidemic, with hotels taking full responsibility for information, medical needs and supplies. Xiao Yaxing is too busy to do anything about it. Usually, she is woken up by a phone call at 8 am and can not go to sleep until 1 pm.

Zhao Min was born and raised in Wuhan, near the Union Hospital. On January 25, he opened his empty room to the hospital's medical staff for free. He made the decision with little thought. "When I see doctors and nurses sleeping on the floor of my office, I always want to do something. "

A number of hotel owners interviewed by Caijing said that in addition to providing rooms and handling reception, they also need to clean and disinfect the public areas of the hotel and supply basic materials. All this time, Liu Dong and his partner were sleeping in the hotel, "two bosses doing their own work, sterilizing every day, risking everything to get supplies. "

The alliance continues to fight despite a number of hotels in the middle pulling out due to operational risks. February 25, the alliance development of the "Sun and moon with the city" medical hotel platform to achieve online matching of medical accommodation demand and supply. Less than 12 hours after launch, 28 hotels have registered, offering a total of 1,042 rooms, and health care workers have posted accommodation requirements for 34.

A lot of the footage is warm. Zhou Qinghui remembered clearly that on the evening of the New Year's Eve, a medical staff, from more than ten kilometers away, arrived at the hotel on foot in three hours. Meanwhile, a bridge across the Yangtze River, three main streets. It struck her, "take off the white coat. He's only eighteen or nineteen. "

Wei Ran was impressed by a doctor nicknamed "Mei Chao Feng" . Dr. May was thirty-something, warm-hearted, and always smiling. He set the store in motion, as if he could drive the fire department and pick up supplies. Once, the hotel's microwave broke because of overload work, he to buy a new, driving around the city, one after another.

Ordinary people who do not know each other will pass on their good intentions in silence. There is little direct communication between health care workers and hotel owners to avoid cross-contamination. But when they do, they smile at each other and then they leave. It's a sign of mutual encouragement.

Once, Zhou Qinghui went upstairs to a doctor to send a meal, the other side carefully will crack open more than 20 centimeters, in the process there is no small talk, but the half-open door, and want to talk and stop the eyes let her fully feel each other's gratitude.

In the eyes of these hoteliers, health care workers are the first line of defense against the virus. Once that line is breached, the city will be in jeopardy. To guard them is to guard themselves.

2

Borrow money to live

2

Borrow money to live

More than most people realize, it's a long game.

Zhao Min spent 32 days at his hotel, and was confined to the front desk, which is now just 30 square meters, where he sat in his usual chair behind his desk for most of the day. But in and out of the medical staff, glass door outside the deserted street and constantly remind him, this is the virus raging Wuhan.

The first two weeks were rough. Paramedics work irregular hours, "any time" , and Zhao Min's entire rest time is between 3:00 a.m. and 6:30 a.m. in order to open the door for them. The situation was alleviated at a later stage. "You know each other well enough to help each other open the door. "

It's been a long 32 days, and the lack of regular breaks is just the beginning. One hotelier said the biggest burden was financial stress. In his case, the monthly water and electricity bill alone is more than 20,000 yuan, and in the absence of income at the moment, is indeed a large expenditure.

Zhao Min now wakes up every day with a loan of more than 200,000 yuan, and in order to maintain a normal flow of funds, he has raised a sum of money from relatives to temporarily cover the shortfall.

Hotel owner Zhou Qinghui also told the "financial" reporter, she is also looking for some low-interest loans to maintain the operation of the hotel.

"To borrow money to live. " This is the current situation of many hotel owners. Li Chao told Caijing that the main subsidies for these small and medium sized hotels now come from the commission free policies of CTRIP, flying pig and other platforms. As for government subsidies, Zhou said, there are some framework documents, but no official announcement has been made.

In a state of constant consumption, Zhao Min's mind changed subtly -- as if he were becoming more aware that money was important. At first some people came to donate money, he refused, "the medical staff in the front line, I do this thing how ashamed to take money? "

The second time he hesitated, "I'm really short of money" ; the third time, after much deliberation, he decided to accept, "the cleaning lady is living on her salary. "

In addition, most of the individual hotels can not apply for the relevant subsidies from the Public Welfare Fund, "It is often very difficult to get subsidies because of the high compliance requirements and complicated procedures for charitable funds and the fact that these hotels do not register the details and documents of receiving medical care in advance, " said a person familiar with the matter.

Survival is more important than anything. Zhou Qinghui flashed in mind the idea of layoffs, she did not dare to think, but in the worst step to come, in advance and management to prepare. "One of the vice presidents broke down in tears when he heard about the possibility of layoffs and pay cuts, " she said.

In the situation of running out of food and ammunition, most small and medium-sized hotels want to be requisitioned by hospitals and the government. A small requisition letter means that disinfection, supplies and staffing of hotels will be ensured, later it was promised some financial compensation.

On February 2, the COVID-19 issued a notice on strengthening the isolation, treatment and management of patients with fever, suspected patients with fever and close contacts. Cities, states and counties immediately requisitioned resources such as hotels, hotels and guest houses with relatively independent locations, little impact on the surrounding environment, water, electricity and clean sewage protection conditions, and quickly converted them into centralized isolation points, the notice said.

Ms. Zhou said that being requisitioned by the government was the best option at the moment, but she tried to submit an application and nothing happened. According to "CAIJING" reporters understand, the government requisitioned most of the high-star, chain hotels. A hotel owner said the government will give priority to large, well-equipped hotels, close to designated hospitals, isolation points.

Unlike unqualified hotels, Zhao Min had received five calls, but he was faced with a dilemma.

Once requisitioned, the hotel's medical staff will be cleared out. He admitted that in the economic pressure so big situation, there was hesitation, finally chose to stick, "it is really unbearable. "

For those who stayed, the difficulties came one after another. Zhao Min's hotel is located in a residential area, which some community workers and residents can not understand, this will greatly increase the possibility of infection with the community. "The way they talk, some people think I'm doing good things, some people even think I'm looking for trouble. "

Tao Kang's situation is even more difficult. "The community was not allowed to receive medical staff and workers from Thor Mountain, " he said. But he did, taking into account the harsh working conditions of the workers, who were not properly housed, "Some of them haven't bathed in almost a week, " he said, leading his apartment in the Haitian building to be shut down on Feb. 18 after a community forced it to cut off electricity and water.

Where's the money coming from? How long can cash flow last? What about the staff? What about the future of the hotel? The sudden outbreak threw all the problems at the hotel people. It doesn't get any harder than this. Zhao Min said, can only day by day, can not borrow money, when the sale of the house to sell the house, the hotel to the hotel.

Nationwide occupancy fell to 17 percent on Jan. 26, according to STR data. CICC research reports that catering, hotels, tourism, non-essential retail businesses suffered more obvious short-term performance, but the overall trend is "first depressed then rising. ". Compared with SARS, the number of domestic tourists decreased by 1% in 2003, but increased by 27% in 2004. The Star Hotel RevPAR decreased by 3% in 2003, but increased by 16% in 2004.

The year 2020 is challenging, but it is also inevitable. Before the Dawn, these hotel owners braved the risk and completed time and time again "retrograde. ". Tao Kang is a veteran, and his love for the country and the city is in his bones. After the hotel was forced to close down, he submitted a volunteer application for prevention and control, after a month of hard waiting, was finally requisitioned, Wuhan streets to become one of the numerous guard duty officers. "What I have done is far from enough, " he told CAIJING

Zhao Min and Wei ran were pseudonyms
